metadata.name: A Clock #97
metadata.description:
This generative token is based on a project I originally coded in late 2014, possibly my first creative project in JavaScript during graduate school at NYU ITP, which has run here since then: https://rossgoodwin.com/clock

The text in this case is not generated, but rather (legally) snipped from public domain e-books on Project Gutenberg (https://gutenberg.org/), and recontextualized as a real-time clock.

The editions vary in color palette and font choice, each with unique text for every minute determined by the clock's unique hash. For nearly all word/phrase blocks in the template system, there exist 512 possible excerpts you could receive, and countless possible combinations thereof. Additionally, 16 possible color palettes, 8 possible fonts, and many bezel types will determine your clock's visual appearance.

Unlike my original 2014 iteration, I wrote this clock in Vanilla JS with zero dependencies. (Largely, that's thanks to eight additional years of programming experience.) As a result, it's faster (once loaded) and more responsive as well.

metadata.name: Dump of links #55
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork.
A blind spot in the metaverse full of junk broken links. Like dead neurons, they were left out of the system. Now they look for the closest thing to oxygen, and in a sonorous broken prelude, achieve synchro, so that one or at least two escape.

The work has 3 moments:
I. "Preludio en el fondo"
II. "Respiración de rotos"
III. "Grita y quema"

Original processed piano, flute and electronic samplers.
((click to start sound))

[s] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)

metadata.name: Magnolia Portrait #127
metadata.description:
Inspired by observation of the incessantly-rooted Pteridophyte and Magnolia, the cognominal series, “Magnolia”, portrays a manifestation of layers of constant streams crossing dynamically in a flow. Through years of growing in fluxed vapor, its knots and roots construct organized and rhythmic patterns within chaotic orders. From two-dimensional layouts to three-dimensional composition, “Magnolia” absorbs its fundamental image, and extend it even further — creating the core of generative artwork.

Press "s" to download

metadata.name: the Horizon #55
metadata.description:
I am interested in and pay attention to repeating patterns in nature. Searching for the possibility of depicting this rhythm, texture, and space opens this opportunity as a new experience for me. And how can I convert time to image? In this work, I have depicted the circle of wandering, like the sun that fluctuates in every horizon and climate, sometimes hot and tense and sometimes its rays like the morning breeze caressing our face, calling us to a new beginning. Where is your sun on the horizon, and what time is it in your world?
Made in p5js
Created July 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi
